    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1901-02-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1901-02-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="251"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d251">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hill</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Powell</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1901-02-08">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 8, 1901</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 452.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to your No. 822, of October 10, last,
                    relative to the alleged right of the Haitian Government to impose higher duties
                    on United States vessels carrying French goods than on French vessels, I have to
                    say that you may advise the Government of Haiti that this Government is of
                    opinion that Article X of the convention of 1864 between the United States and
                    Haiti is quite independent of Article XI and creates absolute rights, which this
                    Government can not fail to insist upon. Should, therefore, any higher charges be
                    collected on American tonnage than that of any other country they will be
                    reclaimed.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">David J. Hill</hi>,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
